Exploratory Data Analysis

Now that the dataframe is relatively clean, we are ready to explore and analyze the dataset of 3805 movies by answering to the questions already asked.

Question 1: What kinds of properties are associated with most and less successful movies?

To answer to this question, i will first calculate the financial benefit realized by each movie, by substracting the budget adjusted (accounting for inflation overtime) from the revenue adjusted. We say that there is a profit when revenue generated from a movie exceeds the expenses, costs, and taxes involved in sustaining the activity in question and vice versa for losses.

In[3]:
df['profit'] = df['revenue_adj'] - df['budget_adj']
In[4]:
def min_max(x):
    highest = df[x].idxmax()
    highest_details = pd.DataFrame(df.loc[highest])

    lowest = df[x].idxmin()
    lowest_details = pd.DataFrame(df.loc[lowest])  
    
    print('Movie which has highest '+x+' : ', df['original_title'][highest])
    print('Movie which has lowest '+x+' : ', df['original_title'][lowest])
    
    return pd.concat([highest_details, lowest_details], axis=1)

But to further justify this finding, causality tests should be conducted.

6. What is the statistical relationship between budget and profit?

In[31]:
fig2 = sns.jointplot(data = df, x = 'budget_adj', y = 'profit', kind = 'scatter')
fig2.fig.suptitle('Correlation between budget and profit');
print("Correlation between Profit and Budget : ",data_corr.loc['profit','budget_adj'])

Correlation between Profit and Budget :  0.40179696213602184

The correlation coefficient between profit and budget is 0.40. This indicates a moderate positive relationship between the two variables. In other words, as the budget increases, profit tends to increase as well. However, since the value is not very high, the relationship is not strong meaning other factors beyond budget also play an important role in determining profit.

2. Which genres are more profitable overall?

In[63]:
df_split['profit'] = pd.to_numeric(df_split['profit'], errors='coerce')
profit_and_genres_df = df_split[['profit', 'genres']]
mean_profit_vs_genre_df = profit_and_genres_df.groupby('genres')['profit'].mean()
mean_profit_vs_genre_df = mean_profit_vs_genre_df.sort_values(ascending=False)

sns.set_style("ticks")

plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
mean_profit_vs_genre_df.plot(
    kind='barh',
    color=sns.color_palette("Purples_r", n_colors=len(mean_profit_vs_genre_df))
)

plt.title('Genres Classification by Average Profit', fontsize=18, color='black', weight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Average Profit (USD)', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Genre', fontsize=12)

plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
plt.show()

Even that, "Drama" genres are the most frequent genre produced overall, but the most profitable one is "Animation". So the top 5 most profitable genres of movies from 1960 to 2015 are:

  • Animation,
  • Adventure,
  • Family,
  • Fantasy,
  • Science Fiction.

3. Which genres are more profitable from year to year?

In this part, i will focus on the top 5 most profitable genres found in the last part to investigate which is the more profitable genre from year to year.

In[74]:
df_split['profit'] = pd.to_numeric(df_split['profit'], errors='coerce')
df_split['release_year'] = pd.to_datetime(df_split['release_date'], errors='coerce').dt.year
df_split = df_split[df_split['release_year'].between(1960, 2015)]

top5_genres = ['Animation', 'Adventure', 'Family', 'Fantasy', 'Science Fiction']
df_top5 = df_split[df_split['genres'].isin(top5_genres)]
profit_top5_over_time = df_top5.groupby(['release_year','genres'])['profit'].sum().unstack().fillna(0)

sns.set_style("whitegrid")
plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))

colors = sns.color_palette("Set2", n_colors=5) 
profit_top5_over_time.plot(marker='o', linewidth=2, color=colors)

plt.title('Profit of Top Genres Over Time', fontsize=18, color='black', weight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Release Year', fontsize=14, color='black')
plt.ylabel('Total Profit (USD)', fontsize=14, color='black')
plt.legend(title='Genres', fontsize=12)
plt.show()

<Figure size 1200x800 with 0 Axes>

Most profitable Genres varies quite a lot from year to year and have known an upward in recent years. In 2015, Advanture is the most profitable genre followed by Science Fiction in the second position and Family movies in the third position.

5. What is the evolution of the genres according to popularity from year to year?

In[78]:
df_split['profit'] = pd.to_numeric(df_split['profit'], errors='coerce')
df_split['release_year'] = pd.to_datetime(df_split['release_date'], errors='coerce').dt.year
df_split = df_split[df_split['release_year'].between(1960, 2015)]
top5_genres = ['Animation', 'Adventure', 'Family', 'Fantasy', 'Science Fiction']
df_top5 = df_split[df_split['genres'].isin(top5_genres)]

# -----------------------------
# Popularity
# -----------------------------
genre_pop_df = df_top5.groupby(['genres', 'release_year'], as_index=False)['popularity'].mean()

plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
colors = sns.color_palette("Set2", n_colors=5)

for i, genre in enumerate(top5_genres):
    data = genre_pop_df[genre_pop_df.genres==genre]
    plt.plot(data.release_year, data.popularity, marker='o', linewidth=2, color=colors[i], label=genre)

plt.xlabel("Release Year", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Average Popularity", fontsize=14)
plt.title('Evolution of Genres According to Popularity (1960-2015)', fontsize=18, weight='bold')
plt.legend(title='Genres', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# -----------------------------
# Profit
# -----------------------------
profit_top5_over_time = df_top5.groupby(['release_year','genres'])['profit'].sum().unstack().fillna(0)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
profit_top5_over_time.plot(marker='o', linewidth=2, color=colors)

plt.title('Profit of Top Genres Over Time (1960-2015)', fontsize=18, weight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Release Year', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Total Profit (USD)', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(title='Genres', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

<Figure size 1200x800 with 0 Axes>
  • Animation, Family, and Fantasy consistently show high popularity among audiences throughout the period.
  • Adventure and Science Fiction display more noticeable fluctuations, with peaks in the 1980s1990s and again in the 2000s.
  • Overall, Animation, Family, and Fantasy remain audience favorites, which partially explains their revenue success.
  • Adventure, Fantasy, and Science Fiction generate the highest profits, especially in the 2000s, driven by large franchises and blockbusters.
  • Animation and Family maintain steady, but relatively lower profits compared to Adventure and Science Fiction, despite being popular.
  • High profit in Adventure and Fantasy aligns with the success of major franchises and big-budget projects.

In[79]:
def extract_data(x):
    all_data = df[x].str.cat(sep = '|')
    all_data = pd.Series(all_data.split('|'))

    return all_data.value_counts(ascending = False)
